      \end{alertblock}

      \begin{alertblock}{Deriving $k_f$}
        Let’s begin with the observation that to achieve $\theta_l^k = \pi/2$ for all $l \in \{0,1,2,\dots,2^{k-1}\}$ from equation~\eqref{eqn:theta}, the areas of two subdivisions must be equal. In other words, in that particular division, $\Delta f(x)$ must approach~$0$. Now, let’s introduce an error term, $\epsilon_f$, ensuring that the derivative of $f(x)$ in any region $[x, x+\Delta x]$ does not vary by more than an infinitesimal fraction~$\epsilon_f$. Then, we proceed to solve for~$\Delta x$.
        $$\Delta x = \frac{1}{2^{k_f-1}} \Rightarrow k_f = \Big\lceil \log_2\frac{1}{\Delta x} \Big\rceil + 1.$$
        $$\left| f'(x+\Delta x) - f'(x) \right| \le \epsilon_f$$

        Taylor expansion:
        $$f'(x + \Delta x) = f'(x) + f''(x)\,\Delta x + \frac{f'''(\xi)}{2} \Delta x^2$$
        $$\left| f'(x+\Delta x) - f'(x) \right| = \left| f''(x)\,\Delta x + \frac{f'''(\xi)}{2} \Delta x^2 \right|$$
        $$\left| f''(x) \, \Delta x \right| \le \epsilon_f$$
        $$\Delta x \le \frac{\epsilon_f}{f''(x)}$$

        Hence, the target $\Delta x$ such that the derivative $f'(x)$ does not vary more than an infinitesimal fraction $\epsilon_f$ over any interval $[x, x+\Delta x]$ is given by
        $$\Delta x = \frac{\epsilon_f}{\sup_{x \le \xi \le x+\Delta x} \left| f''(\xi) \right|}$$
        where $\sup_{x \le \xi <= x+\delta x} \left| f''(\xi) \right|$ is the supremum of the absolute value of the second derivative over the interval $[x, x+\Delta x]$.
      \end{alertblock}

